The company said its core headline earnings from continuing operations stood at $3 billion, or 694 cents per share, in the year to end-March, compared with $2.4 billion or 553 cents per share the year before. JOHANNESBURG - South African media and e-commerce giant Naspers on Friday reported a 25% rise in annual core headline earnings, thanks to reduced losses at its e-commerce business. The company said its core headline earnings from continuing operations stood at $3 billion, or 694 cents per share, in the year to end-March, compared with $2.4 billion or 553 cents per share the year before. Naspers had already flagged that its headline earnings and earnings per share would rise substantially. Core headline EPS is Naspersâ€™ main profit measure that strips out non-operational and one-off items.